org.garret.perst
Interface MultidimensionalIndex<T>

All Superinterfaces:
java.util.Collection<T>, java.io.Externalizable, ILoadable, IPersistent, IResource, IStoreable, ITable<T>, java.lang.Iterable<T>, java.io.Serializable
public interface MultidimensionalIndex<T>
extends IPersistent, IResource, ITable<T>

Interface of multidimensional index. The main idea of this index is to provide efficient search of object using multiple search criteria, for example "select from StockOptions where Symbol between 'AAB' and 'ABC' and Price > 100 and Volume between 1000 and 10000". Each component of the object is represented as separate dimension in the index.

getHeight

int getHeight()
Get height of the tree. Height of the tree can be used by application to determine when tree structure is no optimal and tree should be reconstructed using optimize method.

Returns:
height of the tree

iterator

java.util.Iterator<T> iterator()
Get iterator for traversing all objects in the index. Objects are iterated in the ascent key order. This iterator supports remove() method.

iterator

IterableIterator<T> iterator(T pattern)
Get iterator through objects matching specified pattern object. All fields which are part of multidimensional index and which values in pattern object is not null are used as filter for index members.

Parameters:
pattern - object which is used as search pattern, non null values of components of this object forms search condition
Returns:
iterator through index members which field values are equal to correspondent non-null fields of pattern object

iterator

IterableIterator<T> iterator(T low,
                             T high)
Get iterator through objects which field values belongs to the range specified by correspondent fields of low and high objects.

Parameters:
low - pattern object specifying inclusive low boundary for field values. If there is no low boundary for some particular field it should be set to null. For scalar types (like int) you can use instead minimal possible value, like Integer.MIN_VALUE. If low is null, then low boundary is not specified for all fields.
high - pattern object specifying inclusive high boundary for field values. If there is no high boundary for some particular field it should be set to null. For scalar types (like int) you can use instead maximal possible value, like Integer.MAX_VALUE. If high is null, then high boundary is not specified for all fields.
Returns:
iterator through index members which field values are belongs to the range specified by correspondent fields of low and high objects

optimize

void optimize()
Optimize index to make search more efficient. This operation cause complete reconstruction of the index and so may take a long time. Also please notice that this method doesn't build the ideally balanced tree - it just reinserts elements in the tree in random order
